{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/generating-poisson-distributions-with-shiny-web-apps-9c3352a006ab", "time": 1683012366.906983, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/generating-poisson-distributions-with-shiny-web-apps-9c3352a006ab/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Generating Poisson Distributions with Shiny Web Apps | by Michael Grogan | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Generating Poisson Distributions with Shiny Web Apps", "description": "A Poisson distribution allows us to visualise the probability of an event occurring within a given time interval. The events must be independent of each other. Let\u2019s take an example of hotel\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://michael-grogan.com", "anchor_text": "michael-grogan.com", "paragraph_index": 23}], "all_paragraphs": ["A Poisson distribution allows us to visualise the probability of an event occurring within a given time interval. The events must be independent of each other.", "Some examples of this could be:", "Let\u2019s take an example of hotel cancellations (data and research from Antonio, Almeida and Nunes, available from the References section below).", "Suppose that for a given week, a hotel can expect a certain number of booking cancellations. Based on the first dataset in the study (H1), a hotel can expect an average of 115 booking cancellations per week.", "From the above, we can see that the hotel could expect about a minimum of 90 cancellations per week, and a maximum of 150 cancellations per week.", "However, the advantage of a Shiny Web App whereby l (our lambda value) can be manipulated is that it allows us to analyse a range of different scenarios on the fly.", "For instance, another hotel in the study (H2) had an average of 287 cancellations per week. Let\u2019s change the lambda value and see how this affects the analysis.", "In this instance, we see that we have a range of approximately 230\u2013330 cancellations per week. This would allow a hotel manager to conduct a probability assessment of the approximate number of hotel cancellations that could be expected per week.", "That said, the above Poisson distribution could be used to analyse any problem \u2014 it is simply a matter of knowing the lambda value and adjusting the x-axis if necessary to account for the overall range of values for the particular set of data in question.", "Why don\u2019t you try this simulation for yourself?", "To generate the Shiny Web App, do the following:", "4. In server.R, paste the following:", "5. When that has been done, click Run App in the top right-hand corner of the console:", "You will now be presented with a dynamic Poisson Distribution whereby l (lambda) can be adjusted on the fly :)", "Now, suppose that you wish to adjust the scales. What if you are working on a much smaller problem, e.g. you receive an average of 10 emails per day and want to know the minimum and maximum for this interval?", "In ui.R, let\u2019s set the maximum lambda value to 20.", "In server.R, the value of x and the sequence can be adjusted. Let\u2019s set the maximum range to 20.", "Here is what the distribution will now look like assuming l = 10:", "Poisson Distributions can be very useful when analysing the probability of a certain number of events occurring in a given time interval \u2014 and even more useful when we can do a dynamic analysis using Shiny Web Apps!", "Many thanks for reading this article, and any questions or feedback appreciated.", "You can also find the link to my GitHub (MGCodesandStats/shiny-web-apps) with the included code scripts below, along with other useful references.", "Disclaimer: This article is written on an \u201cas is\u201d basis and without warranty. It was written with the intention of providing an overview of data science concepts, and should not be interpreted as professional advice in any way.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data Science Consultant with expertise in economics, t